<section class="hero">
  <h1>Take your group chat<br />to Eleven.</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Eleven works like the messenger you already use. Groups, photos,
    reactions, replies. No ads, no tracking, no big-tech company reading
    over your shoulder. Just you and the people you invited.
  </p>
  <div class="cta">
    <a class="btn btn-primary" href="#get">Get Eleven</a>
    <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/security/">How it stays private</a>
  </div>
  <p class="fine">
    Invite-only — there's no public sign-up. Someone already in a chat sends you
    a link.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="pains" aria-label="Why Eleven exists">
  <h2>Ever wondered&hellip;</h2>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why is chatting to your friends run by big tech?</h3>
    <p>
      A group chat with your actual friends doesn't need a social network
      wrapped around it. It doesn't need an algorithm deciding what you see,
      and it definitely doesn't need a business model that runs on knowing
      who you talk to.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why do you need a mobile number to talk to people you already know?</h3>
    <p>
      Your phone number is an identity you hand over before you've even said
      hello. Eleven skips accounts entirely — you join with a secret link
      from someone already inside.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Why choose between owning your chat and actually enjoying it?</h3>
    <p>
      Self-hosting usually means wrestling with servers and losing the
      polish along the way. Eleven is one small server you run yourself,
      wrapped in an app that feels like the ones you already use every day.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="features" aria-label="What makes Eleven different">
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Feels like home</h3>
    <p>
      Groups and DMs, photos, reactions, replies, link previews, push
      notifications. Everything you'd expect from a modern messenger.
      Nothing new to learn.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>No logins, no passwords</h3>
    <p>
      No phone number, no email, no account of any kind. Just a one-time
      secret link. Nothing to remember, nothing to phish, nothing to leak.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Yours to run</h3>
    <p>
      Each chat is its own tiny private server. Set one up for your
      friends, your family, your kid's class group, whatever it is. You
      decide who's in. Nobody else gets a say.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="feature">
    <h3>Private by design</h3>
    <p>
      Messages are end-to-end encrypted. Even the server can't read them.
      <a href="/security/">See how the security model works&nbsp;&rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="pains" aria-label="Eleven and AI">
  <h2>Where AI fits</h2>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>Built and audited by the best models there are</h3>
    <p>
      Eleven is built with the latest AI models, and audited by them too,
      including a security review by Claude&nbsp;Fable. We're in beta with
      the source open, so nobody has to take our word for any of that.
      Check the code yourself.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="pain">
    <h3>In your chats only if you invite it</h3>
    <p>
      You choose how much AI touches your server: an assistant in one
      group, a quiet bot in another, or none at all. Nothing is on by
      default.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

